.SS Core state model
.sp
Most C routines receive two pointers:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \fBstruct cmdline_data *cmd\fP
Values requested by the user or read from a parameter file. Treat this as
configuration. It contains items such as \fBsearchMethod\fP, histogram sizes,
input/output names, verbosity, and option strings.
.TP
.B \fBstruct global_data *gd\fP
Values computed during the run. Treat this as mutable execution state. It
owns histogram buffers, input catalog metadata, output paths, timing
counters, tree statistics, and allocation flags used during cleanup.
.UNINDENT
.sp
The large catalog and tree tables are declared as project globals in
\fBinclude/globaldefs.h\fP:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \fBbodytable[MAXITEMS]\fP
Per\-catalog body arrays.
.TP
.B \fBroottable[MAXITEMS]\fP
One tree root per loaded catalog.
.TP
.B \fBnodetablescanlev[MAXITEMS]\fP and \fBnodetablescanlev_root[MAXITEMS]\fP
Flattened node tables used by scan\-level traversal and diagnostics.
.UNINDENT
.sp
The body/cell hierarchy is defined in \fBinclude/datastruc_defs.h\fP\&. A \fBbody\fP
contains a \fBnode\fP named \fBbodynode\fP and a body id. A \fBcell\fP contains a
\fBnode\fP named \fBcellnode\fP, a size, a linked \fBmore\fP pointer, and \fBNSUB\fP
subcells. The macros in that header, for example \fBPos(x)\fP, \fBMass(x)\fP,
\fBRadius(x)\fP, and \fBSubp(x)\fP, are the intended field access style throughout
the C code.
.SS Tree and search lifecycle
.sp
\fBMakeTree\fP in \fBsource/treeload.c\fP starts with \fBnewtree\fP and a root cell,
then loads bodies into subcells using \fBloadbody\fP and \fBsubindex\fP\&. After
insertion, \fBhackcellprop\fP computes cell\-level properties used by the search,
\fBthreadtree\fP links traversal order, and \fBscanLevel\fP prepares node tables
for level\-based operations.
.sp
\fBsearchcalc_normal_sincos\fP in \fBsource/search.c\fP is the default search path
for \fBsearchMethod=tree\-omp\-sincos\fP/\fBoctree\-sincos\-omp\fP style runs. It:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
Initializes global and per\-thread histogram workspaces.
.IP 2. 3
Runs an OpenMP loop over pivot bodies from the selected pivot catalog.
.IP 3. 3
Walks the scanning catalog tree with \fBnormal_walktree_sincos\fP\&.
.IP 4. 3
Uses acceptance/rejection helpers from \fBsource/cballsutils.c\fP to decide
whether a body/cell or cell/cell pair contributes.
.IP 5. 3
Accumulates 2PCF and, when enabled at compile time, 3PCF Chebyshev/sine/cosine
components.
.IP 6. 3
Merges thread\-local histograms back into \fBgd\fP\&.
.UNINDENT
.SS Histogram ownership
.sp
Histogram buffers are allocated during startup and search initialization, then
freed through the \fBEndRun_FreeMemory_*\fP routines in \fBsource/cballsio.c\fP\&.
The important ownership rule is: if a new allocation is attached to \fBcmd\fP or
\fBgd\fP, it needs a matching allocation flag or an existing cleanup stage that
cannot miss it. This is especially important for the Python wrapper, because
\fBcballs.struct_cleanup\fP calls the granular C cleanup routines instead of only
exiting the process.
.sp
Common histogram outputs include:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \fBhistNN\fP
Neighbor count histogram.
.TP
.B \fBhistCF\fP
Correlation\-function style output derived from counts.
.TP
.B \fBhistXi2pcf\fP
Two\-point correlation function output.
.TP
.B \fBhistZetaM*\fP and \fBmhistZetaM*\fP
Three\-point/Chebyshev multipole outputs, split by sine/cosine component and
multipole index when the corresponding compile\-time options are enabled.
.UNINDENT
.SS Adding or changing parameters
.sp
To add a user\-visible parameter:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
Add the default, description, and optional short name in
\fBinclude/cmdline_defs.h\fP\&.
.IP 2. 3
Add fields to \fBstruct cmdline_data\fP in \fBinclude/cmdline_data.h\fP if the
value needs to persist.
.IP 3. 3
Read the parameter in \fBReadParametersCmdline\fP and \fBReadParameterFile\fP in
\fBsource/startrun.c\fP\&.
.IP 4. 3
Print it from \fBPrintParameterFile\fP so generated parameter snapshots remain
reproducible.
.IP 5. 3
Validate derived constraints in \fBCheckParameters\fP when invalid
combinations would otherwise fail later.
.IP 6. 3
If the parameter is exposed to Python, mirror it in \fBpython/ccballys.pxd\fP
and set or document it in \fBpython/cballys.pyx\fP\&.
.UNINDENT
.SS Adding input/output formats
.sp
Input format names are converted to integer tags by
\fBinfilefmt_string_to_int\fP in \fBsource/cballsio.c\fP\&. Add a new tag in the same
style as the existing formats, implement the parser near the other
\fBinputdata_*\fP functions, and add the switch case in \fBInputData\fP or
\fBInputData_all_in_one\fP\&.
.sp
Output formats follow the matching pattern through
\fBoutfilefmt_string_to_int\fP, \fBoutputdata\fP, and the \fBoutputdata_*\fP helpers.
Keep filename construction in \fBsetFilesDirs\fP/\fBsetFilesDirs_log\fP so command
line, tests, and Python runs all agree on output paths.
.SS Adding search methods
.sp
Search\-method selection happens in two places:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
\fBsearch_method_string_to_int\fP in \fBsource/startrun.c\fP maps user strings
to integer constants.
.IP 2. 3
\fBEvalHist\fP in \fBsource/cballs.c\fP switches on \fBgd\->searchMethod_int\fP and
calls the concrete implementation.
.UNINDENT
.sp
New search methods usually need prototypes in \fBinclude/protodefs.h\fP, compile
settings in the Makefiles or add\-on make fragments, and output handling in
\fBsource/cballs.c\fP only if they produce different histogram families.
.SS Add\-on sockets
.sp
Core files contain \fB//B socket:\fP blocks guarded by \fB#ifdef ADDONS\fP\&. These
blocks include generated or configured files such as \fB*_include.h\fP so optional
modules can add fields, prototypes, switch cases, and setup logic without
editing every core file manually. When adding an add\-on, keep its ownership
localized under \fBaddons/<name>/\fP and document which socket files it expects to
be copied or generated.
.SS Python wrapper notes
.sp
The wrapper class \fBcballs\fP in \fBpython/cballys.pyx\fP keeps a Python parameter
dictionary in \fBself._pars\fP\&. \fBRun\fP converts that dictionary into
\fBfile_content\fP, calls \fBinput_read_from_file\fP, then advances through
\fBStartRun_Common\fP, \fBPrintParameterFile\fP, \fBSetNumberThreads\fP, and
\fBMainLoop\fP according to the requested dependency level.
.sp
Getter methods such as \fBgetrBins\fP, \fBgetHistNN\fP, \fBgetHistXi2pcf\fP, and
\fBgetHistZetaMsincos\fP copy C arrays into NumPy arrays. They assume the relevant
run stage has already completed and that \fBsizeHistN\fP still matches the
allocated histogram dimensions.
.sp
When changing C struct fields consumed by Python, update both
\fBpython/ccballys.pxd\fP and the getter or setup code in \fBpython/cballys.pyx\fP\&.
The wrapper intentionally exposes only a subset of the C structs; avoid adding
fields to the \fB\&.pxd\fP unless Python needs direct access.
.SS Generated and vendored code
.sp
The repository includes generated Sphinx output under \fBdocs/_build\fP and large
vendored libraries under \fBaddons/\fP\&. Prefer editing the source \fB\&.rst\fP files,
core \fBsource/\fP and \fBinclude/\fP code, or add\-on source fragments rather than
generated HTML/LaTeX or third\-party library internals.
.SH ADDON'S
.sp
Add\-ons extend cBalls with optional search methods, catalog formats, and
supporting libraries without making every core file permanently depend on those
features. They are enabled at compile time through \fBMakefile_settings\fP and the
add\-on make fragments under \fBaddons/\fP\&.
.SS Include files
.sp
Core headers and modules contain guarded \fB//B socket:\fP blocks such as:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
#ifdef ADDONS
#include \(dqprotodefs_include.h\(dq
#endif
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
An add\-on uses these include sockets to add prototypes, struct fields,
parameter definitions, switch cases, and implementation hooks. Keep add\-on
specific declarations in the add\-on include files rather than editing unrelated
core code.
.sp
Common socket targets include:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \fBcmdline_defs_include.h\fP
Adds new command\-line parameters.
.TP
.B \fBprotodefs_include.h\fP
Adds prototypes that must be visible across C modules.
.TP
.B \fBglobaldefs_include_*.h\fP and \fBglobal_data_include_*.h\fP
Adds globals or run\-state fields required by the add\-on.
.TP
.B \fBcballs_include_*.h\fP, \fBstartrun_include_*.h\fP, \fBcballsio_include_*.h\fP
Adds search\-method dispatch, startup, and I/O cases.
.UNINDENT
.SS Source files
.sp
Each add\-on should keep its implementation and build fragment in its own
subdirectory, for example \fBaddons/cfitsio\fP, \fBaddons/gadget_io\fP,
\fBaddons/kdtree_box_omp\fP, or \fBaddons/octree_box_omp\fP\&. The add\-on
\fBReadme.txt\fP and \fBTo_add_in_Makefile_addons\fP files explain which fragments
must be included in the top\-level add\-on build.
.sp
When adding a new search add\-on, wire it through the same conceptual path as a
core search method:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
Define the command\-line search string and integer method tag.
.IP 2. 3
Add parameter parsing or validation hooks if the method needs extra options.
.IP 3. 3
Add the method\(aqs prototype through the prototype socket.
.IP 4. 3
Add the \fBEvalHist\fP switch case through the \fBcballs\fP socket.
.IP 5. 3
Make sure any method\-specific allocations are released by an existing or new
cleanup hook.
.UNINDENT
.sp
When adding a new I/O add\-on, add the format string conversion, the parser or
writer implementation, and the \fBInputData\fP/\fBOutputData\fP switch case through
the I/O sockets.
.SH PYTHON INTERFACE
.sp
The Python extension is implemented by \fBpython/cballys.pyx\fP and declared to
Cython through \fBpython/ccballys.pxd\fP\&. It wraps the same C lifecycle used by the
\fBcballs\fP executable, but exposes it as a Python class named \fBcballs\fP\&.
.SS Basic lifecycle
.sp
Typical Python use follows this pattern:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
from cballys import cballs

cb = cballs()
cb.set(
    infile=\(dqcatalog.txt\(dq,
    infileformat=\(dqcolumns\-ascii\(dq,
    rootDir=\(dqOutput\(dq,
    options=\(dqcompute\-HistN\(dq,
)
cb.Run()
rbins = cb.getrBins()
xi2 = cb.getHistXi2pcf()
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBset\fP updates the internal parameter dictionary. \fBRun\fP converts that
dictionary into the C \fBfile_content\fP representation, calls the startup
routines, executes the main search, and leaves C\-owned histograms available for
getter methods. \fBclean_all\fP releases C allocations and clears the Python
parameter dictionary.
.SS Run levels
.sp
\fBRun(level=[...])\fP accepts the name of the last C stage the caller needs. The
wrapper expands dependencies automatically. The default level is
\fB[\(dqMainLoop\(dq]\fP, which performs a full calculation. Internally the common stage
order is:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP 1. 3
\fBinput\fP reads Python parameters into C structures.
.IP 2. 3
\fBStartRun_Common\fP validates parameters, initializes state, loads input
catalogs or test data, and allocates memory.
.IP 3. 3
\fBPrintParameterFile\fP writes a reproducible parameter snapshot.
.IP 4. 3
\fBSetNumberThreads\fP applies the OpenMP thread count.
.IP 5. 3
\fBMainLoop\fP builds trees, runs the selected search, and evaluates
histograms.
.UNINDENT
.SS Available getters
.sp
The wrapper exposes small, NumPy\-oriented getters for the C arrays used most
often from notebooks and scripts:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B \fBgetrBins\fP
Radial bin centers or edges as prepared by the C run.
.TP
.B \fBgetHistNN\fP and \fBgetHistCF\fP
Neighbor counts and correlation\-function outputs.
.TP
.B \fBgetHistXi2pcf\fP
Two\-point correlation function array.
.TP
.B \fBgetHistZetaMsincos(m, type)\fP and \fBgetHistZetaM_EE(m)\fP
Two\-dimensional 3PCF/multipole matrices for the requested multipole index.
.UNINDENT
.sp
\fBgetNThreads\fP, \fBgetTheta\fP, \fBgetrsmooth\fP, \fBgetCPUTime\fP, \fBgetVersion\fP,
\fBgetRootDir\fP, and allocation\-flag getters expose selected scalar state from
the underlying C structs.
.SS Cython interface
.sp
\fBpython/ccballys.pxd\fP intentionally declares only the fields and C functions
needed by the wrapper. When a C field is renamed, moved, or newly needed by
Python, update the \fB\&.pxd\fP declaration and the matching logic in
\fBpython/cballys.pyx\fP together.
.sp
Memory is owned by the C code after \fBStartRun_Common\fP\&. The wrapper tracks C
allocation flags and calls the granular \fBEndRun_FreeMemory_*\fP routines from
\fBstruct_cleanup\fP\&. New C allocations that should survive long enough for
Python getters must also be reachable by the cleanup path.
.SS See also
.sp
For a broader map of the C modules and Python wrapper, see
\fI\%Code structure\fP\&.
.SH HANDS ON
.sp
This section describes a practical guide to use \fBcBalls\fP:
.sp
Let us test one of the \X'tty: link https://arxiv.org/pdf/1706.01472'\fI\%Takahashi\fP\X'tty: link' realizations. We download the realization using unix \fBwget\fP command in the terminal:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
wget http://cosmo.phys.hirosaki\-u.ac.jp/takahasi/allsky_raytracing/sub1/nres12/allskymap_nres12r000.zs9.mag.dat
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
Then we will have in our working directory the file \fBallskymap_nres12r000.zs9.mag.dat\fP, 3 Gb in size with ~200 million points distributed on the surface of a unit sphere.
.SH 2-POINT CORRELATION FUNCTIONS
.sp
\fBcBalls\fP can compute 2\-point correlations (2pcf) when counts (N) or a scalar field are involved (like convergence K):
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B NN
It is the normal 2\-point correlation function of number counts (typically
galaxy counts).
.TP
.B KK
So far we have consider that the scalar field is the convergence in weak lensing \ekappa\&. Then this gives the 2\-point kappa\-kappa correlation function.
.UNINDENT
.sp
N represent simple counting and K represent a real scalar field, like convergence in weak lensing.
.SH 3-POINT CORRELATION FUNCTIONS
.sp
\fBcBalls\fP can also compute 3\-point correlations (3pcf) when counts (N) or a scalar field are involved (like convergence \ekappa). In particular to compute the correlation KKK the numerical code use the harmonic base.
.SS Harmonic base
